  6  List folds generalized to `traversable`. Informally, we can think of
  7  `foldl` as a special case of `traverse` where we do not care about the
  8  reconstructed data structure and, in a state monad, we care about the
  9  final state.
 10  
 11  The obvious way to define `foldl` would be to use the state monad but it
 12  is nicer to reason about a more abstract interface with `fold_map` as a
 13  primitive and `fold_map_hom` as a defining property.
 14  
 15  def fold_map {α ω} [has_one ω] [has_mul ω] (f : α → ω) : t α → ω := ...
 16  
 17  lemma fold_map_hom (α β)
 18    [monoid α] [monoid β] (f : α → β) [is_monoid_hom f]
 19    (g : γ → α) (x : t γ) :
 20    f (fold_map g x) = fold_map (f ∘ g) x :=
 21  ...
 22  
 23  `fold_map` uses a monoid ω to accumulate a value for every element of
 24  a data structure and `fold_map_hom` uses a monoid homomorphism to
 25  substitute the monoid used by `fold_map`. The two are sufficient to
 26  define `foldl`, `foldr` and `to_list`. `to_list` permits the
 27  formulation of specifications in terms of operations on lists.
 28  
 29  Each fold function can be defined using a specialized
 30  monoid. `to_list` uses a free monoid represented as a list with
 31  concatenation while `foldl` uses endofunctions together with function
 32  composition.
 33  
 34  The definition through monoids uses `traverse` together with the
 35  applicative functor `const m` (where `m` is the monoid). As an
 36  implementation, `const` guarantees that no resource is spent on
 37  reconstructing the structure during traversal.
 38  
 39  A special class could be defined for `foldable`, similarly to Haskell,
 40  but the author cannot think of instances of `foldable` that are not also
 41  `traversable`.
 42  
 43  -/

 60  variables {α β : Type u}
 61  /--
 62  For a list, foldl f x [y₀,y₁] reduces as follows
 63    calc  foldl f x [y₀,y₁]
 64        = foldl f (f x y₀) [y₁]      : rfl
 65    ... = foldl f (f (f x y₀) y₁) [] : rfl
 66    ... = f (f x y₀) y₁              : rfl
 67  
 68  with f : α → β → α
 69       x : α
 70       [y₀,y₁] : list β
 71  
 72  We can view the above as a composition of functions:
 73  
 74    ... = f (f x y₀) y₁              : rfl
 75    ... = flip f y₁ (flip f y₀ x)    : rfl
 76    ... = (flip f y₁ ∘ flip f y₀) x  : rfl
 77  
 78  We can use traverse and const to construct this composition:
 79  
 80    calc   const.run (traverse (λ y, const.mk' (flip f y)) [y₀,y₁]) x
 81         = const.run ((::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₀) <*> traverse (λ y, const.mk' (flip f y)) [y₁]) x
 82    ...  = const.run ((::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₀) <*> ( (::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₁) <*> traverse (λ y, const.mk' (flip f y)) [] )) x
 83    ...  = const.run ((::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₀) <*> ( (::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₁) <*> pure [] )) x
 84    ...  = const.run ( ((::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₁) <*> pure []) ∘ ((::) <$> const.mk' (flip f y₀)) ) x
 85    ...  = const.run ( const.mk' (flip f y₁) ∘ const.mk' (flip f y₀) ) x
 86    ...  = const.run ( flip f y₁ ∘ flip f y₀ ) x
 87    ...  = f (f x y₀) y₁
 88  
 89  And this is how `const` turns a monoid into an applicative functor and
 90  how the monoid of endofunctions define `foldl`.
 91  -/

134  /--
135  Conceptually, `to_list` collects all the elements of a collection
136  in a list. This idea is formalized by
137  
138    `lemma to_list_spec (x : t α) : to_list x = fold_map free_monoid.mk x`.
139  
140  The definition of `to_list` is based on `foldl` and `list.cons` for
141  speed. It is faster than using `fold_map free_monoid.mk` because, by
142  using `foldl` and `list.cons`, each insertion is done in constant
143  time. As a consequence, `to_list` performs in linear.
144  
145  On the other hand, `fold_map free_monoid.mk` creates a singleton list
146  around each element and concatenates all the resulting lists. In
147  `xs ++ ys`, concatenation takes a time proportional to `length xs`. Since
148  the order in which concatenation is evaluated is unspecified, nothing
149  prevents each element of the traversable to be appended at the end
150  `xs ++ [x]` which would yield a `O(n²)` run time. -/
151  def to_list : t α → list α :=
id                 ┴ ┴   └──┘ ┴
src                      └──┘
typ                ┴ ┴   └──┘ ┴
152  list.reverse ∘ foldl (flip list.cons) []
